comments.text:
I may be looking into this way too far in depth but I absolutely love this 
scene.  Walter thinks Larry is F***ing him the A*** by stealing his money. 
Walter then tries to teach Larry a lesson by smashing what he thinks is 
Larry's car.  Instead, Walter actually shows Larry firsthand what happens 
when you F*** a stranger in the A*** by smashing the neighbor's car (a 
complete stranger). The neighbor then responds by smashing what he thinks 
is Walter's car.  Turns out, the neighbor ends up showing Larry for a 
second time what happens when you F*** a stranger in the A** by smashing 
The Dude's car.  In the end, Walter successfully teaches Larry exactly what 
happens but in a completely backwards way from what was intended.   The 
irony of this whole scene is just brilliant. ﻿

I REALLY like that perspective! Never thought of that! Clever! It may not 
have even been the directors original thought, but the rule with film 
analysis (taking a page from a film reviewer called Rob Ager here) is that 
it is still possible to have a valid insight into a film regardless of the 
directors intention. Ultimately, it is art and at times can be subjective. 
Meanings can be subtle and could even be coming from the directors 
subconscious! So yeah, keep reading in depth into things! You could be 
right .. or not .. who cares, you at least have an interesting point!
